{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569593"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:29:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:29:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22272"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22272"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.24,0.11,0.28,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15237"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108088"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15237"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22272"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90498"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"},{"type":"tags","id":"12954"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40278"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40291"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43762"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108088"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of generalised itch. He has a medical history of stage 4 chronic kidney disease secondary to diabetic nephropathy, hypertension, and type 2 diabetes. His medications include insulin, perindopril, amlodipine, and atorvastatin. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe reports that he has tried using moisturisers, avoiding hot showers, and wearing loose cotton clothing, but the itching persists. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His skin shows mild excoriations on the arms and legs but no rash, lesions, or signs of infection. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical corticosteroid cream","Oral cholestyramine","Ultraviolet B phototherapy","Oral cetirizine","Topical capsaicin"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with pruritus associated with chronic kidney disease (CKD) that has not responded to appropriate non-pharmacological measures. CKD-associated pruritus affects approximately 40% of patients with end-stage renal disease and can significantly impact quality of life. The pathophysiology is complex and multifactorial, involving immune system dysregulation, opioid receptor imbalance, and microinflammation rather than being primarily histamine-mediated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical capsaicin\u003C/strong\u003E is an appropriate next step for this patient with persistent CKD-associated pruritus despite non-pharmacological measures. Capsaicin works by depleting substance P from sensory nerve endings, which reduces itch transmission. It can cause a transient burning sensation upon application, which may limit tolerability in some patients, but this should diminish with continued use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral cetirizine\u003C/strong\u003E and other antihistamines have limited efficacy in CKD-associated pruritus because the condition is not primarily mediated by histamine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical corticosteroid cream\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if there were signs of an inflammatory skin condition, but this patient has generalised pruritus without a rash or specific lesions. Long-term use of topical corticosteroids can lead to skin atrophy and other adverse effects, making them unsuitable for chronic, widespread use in this context.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltraviolet B phototherapy\u003C/strong\u003E has shown efficacy in treating CKD-associated pruritus and may be considered for patients with severe symptoms that do not respond to other treatments. It may be considered after appropriate pharmacological therapy has been trialled.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral cholestyramine\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used for pruritus associated with cholestatic liver disease due to its bile acid-binding properties. It has limited evidence for efficacy in CKD-associated pruritus and can cause gastrointestinal side effects and drug interactions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBefore initiating any pharmacological therapy, it is important to ensure that other potential causes of pruritus have been excluded, such as inadequate dialysis, calcium/phosphate abnormalities, or skin diseases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Topical capsaicin is an effective pharmacological treatment for chronic kidney disease-associated pruritus that persists despite non-pharmacological measures.","Non-pharmacological management of pruritus in chronic kidney disease includes avoiding hot showers, using emollients, and avoiding soaps/detergents.","Antihistamines have limited efficacy in chronic kidney disease-associated pruritus as it is not primarily histamine-mediated."],"references":["Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) Management in Primary Care (5th edition). Kidney Health Australia. 2024. Available from:\u00a0https://assets.kidney.org.au/resources/KHA-CKD-Handbook-5th-Ed-July2024.pdf","Simonsen E, Komenda P, Lerner B, Askin N, Bohm C, Shaw J, Tangri N, Rigatto C. Treatment of Uremic Pruritus: A Systematic Review. Am J Kidney Dis. 2017 Nov;70(5):638-655. doi: 10.1053/j.ajkd.2017.05.018. Epub 2017 Jul 15. Available from: https://www.ajkd.org/article/S0272-6386(17)30781-3/fulltext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90498"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22272"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90498"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-06T15:07:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-06T15:08:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15237"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108088"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":n